#: Game.Levels.SubsetWorld.L10_ExtIntro
msgid "You proved your first set equality using §0! The structure was:\n"
"\n"
"§1\n"
"\n"
"**Why §2 works**: §3 applies the **extensionality** axiom for\n"
"sets: two sets are equal if and only if they have the same elements.\n"
"This converts a single equation into universally quantified membership\n"
"equivalences — exactly the type of claim you can prove element by\n"
"element.\n"
"\n"
"In ordinary math, this proof would read: \"We show the sets are equal\n"
"by double inclusion. If §4 and §5, then certainly §6.\n"
"Conversely, if §7, then also §8 (since §9), so\n"
"§10.\"\n"
"\n"
"**The §11 (focus dot)**: After §12 splits a goal into two\n"
"subgoals, §13 focuses on one at a time. This keeps your proof\n"
"organized — you handle one case completely before moving to the next.\n"
"You will use §14 in nearly every proof that involves §15.\n"
"\n"
"**Dot projections on §16**: If §17, then §18 and\n"
"§19. This is the quickest way to extract one component of a\n"
"conjunction. The same §20/§21 pattern works on §22 (biconditionals)\n"
"too — you will use it later to extract the forward and backward\n"
"implications.\n"
"\n"
"**Destructuring §23**: When a hypothesis is a conjunction §24,\n"
"you can write §25 to introduce and split it in one step,\n"
"instead of §26 followed by §27. This\n"
"shorthand will be especially useful in the next world when working\n"
"with intersections (§28), which are defined as conjunctions.\n"
"\n"
"The §29 tactic is the primary tool for set equality proofs in Lean.\n"
"You will use it frequently throughout this course."
msgstr ""

